    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>School-Prayer Fallacy</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Douglas E McNeil letter rejects notion of some causal connection between bans on school prayer and violence in schools (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I'm getting tired of assertions like that of Representative Ernest Istook Jr. -- ''As prayer has gone out of schools, guns, knives, drugs and gangs have come in'' -- with the unsupported implication that there is some causal connection between these events (''House Rejects Drive to Allow Formal Prayer in the Schools,'' news article, June 5).</p>
        <p>This is the post hoc, ergo propter hoc fallacy.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I'm getting tired of assertions like that of Representative Ernest Istook Jr. -- ''As prayer has gone out of schools, guns, knives, drugs and gangs have come in'' -- with the unsupported implication that there is some causal connection between these events (''House Rejects Drive to Allow Formal Prayer in the Schools,'' news article, June 5).</p>
        <p>This is the post hoc, ergo propter hoc fallacy.</p>
        <p>The association of two events does not prove that one caused the other. We could just as well say, ''After we threw God out of the schools, we put a man on the moon.'' Students may or may not need more faith, but Congress could certainly use more reason.</p>
        <p>DOUGLAS  E. MC NEIL  Baltimore, June 8, 1998</p>
      </block>
